\c 1
\s1 Prologue
\m 
\v 1 The words of the Teacher,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Hebrew “Qohelet” \f* the son of David, king in Jerusalem.
\s1 Motto Introduced
\sd0
\q1 
\v 2 “Vanity of vanities!” says the Teacher,\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Hebrew “Qohelet” \f*
\q2 “Vanity of vanities! All \add is\add* vanity!”
\sd0
\s1 All Toil is Profitless and Repetitious
\sd0
\q1 
\v 3 What does a person gain in all his toil
\q2 with which he toils under the sun?
\q1 
\v 4 A generation goes, and a generation comes,
\q2 but the earth stands forever.
\q1 
\v 5 The sun rises, and the sun goes down;
\q2 to its place it hurries,\f + \fr 1:5 \ft The MT reads “\fq it \ft gasps \fq for breath \ft ,” which is supported by LXX “to draw \fq breath \ft ”; the BHS editors suggest “\fq it \ft returns again” \f* and there it rises again.
\q1 
\v 6 The wind goes to the south and goes around to the north;
\q2 around and around it goes, and on its circuit the wind returns.
\q1 
\v 7 All the streams flow to the sea,
\q2 but the sea is never full;
\q1 to the place where the streams flow,
\q2 there they continue to flow.
\q1 
\v 8 All things toil continuously;\f + \fr 1:8 \ft Or “are wearisome” \f*
\q2 no one can ever finish describing this.\f + \fr 1:8 \ft The MT reads “no one is able to speak.” The BHS editors suggest “no one can finish speaking.” On the basis of internal evidence, the latter is adopted in the translation, since it makes better sense in the light of the immediate context \f*
\q1 The eye is never\f + \fr 1:8 \ft Or “not” \f* satisfied with seeing,
\q2 and the ear is never\f + \fr 1:8 \ft Or “not” \f* filled with hearing.
\q1 
\v 9 What has been—it is what will be;
\q2 what has been done—it is what will be done;
\q3 there is nothing new under the sun.
\q1 
\v 10 There is a thing \add of\add* which it is said, “Look at this! This is new!”
\q2 \add But\add* it already existed in ages past before us.
\q1 
\v 11 There is neither remembrance of former generations,
\q2 nor will there be remembrance of future generations.
\sd0
\s1 Qohelet Introduces His Quest
\m 
\v 12 I, the Teacher,\f + \fr 1:12 \ft Hebrew “Qohelet” \f* \add was\add* king over Israel in Jerusalem. 
\v 13 I applied my mind to seek and to search by wisdom all that is done under the heavens.\f + \fr 1:13 \ft MT reads “under the heavens,” which is supported by LXX; however, several versions (Syriac Peshitta, Aramaic Targum, Latin Vulgate) as well as the Cairo Geniza manuscript read, “under the sun,” cf. 1:3, 9, etc. \f* It \add is\add* a grievous task God has given to ⸤humans⸥.\f + \fr 1:13 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* 
\v 14 I saw all the works that are done under the sun. Look! Everything \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind.
\sd0
\q1 
\v 15 What is twisted cannot be straightened,\f + \fr 1:15 \ft The MT reads the active “to be straight”; however, the BHS editors suggest the passive “to be straightened,” which is supported by LXX, which reflects a passive form \f*
\q2 and what is lacking cannot be counted.\f + \fr 1:15 \ft The MT reads “to be numbered”; however, the BHS editors suggest “to be supplied,” comparing 1:15b with similar wording in the Babylonian Talmud: “May the Almighty replenish your loss” (\fqa b. Berachot \ft 16b) \f*
\sd0
\p 
\v 16 ⸤I said to myself⸥,\f + \fr 1:16 \ft Literally “I myself said to my heart” \f* “Look! I have become great and have increased \add in\add* wisdom more than anyone who ⸤has preceded⸥\f + \fr 1:16 \ft Literally “before me” \f* me over Jerusalem. ⸤I have acquired a great deal of wisdom and knowledge⸥.”\f + \fr 1:16 \ft Literally “And my mind has seen much wisdom and knowledge” \f* 
\v 17 So ⸤I dedicated myself⸥\f + \fr 1:17 \ft Literally “\xt So I \ft gave my heart” \f* to learn about wisdom and \add to\add* learn about delusion and folly. However, I discovered\f + \fr 1:17 \ft Or “I knew” \f* that this also \add is\add* chasing wind.
\sd0
\q1 
\v 18 For in much wisdom \add is\add* much frustration,\f + \fr 1:18 \ft Or “vexation” \f*
\q2 and whoever increases knowledge increases sorrow.
\sd0
\c 2
\s1 Qohelet’s Investigation of Self-Indulgence
\m 
\v 1 I said ⸤to myself⸥,\f + \fr 2:1 \ft Literally “to my heart” \f* “Come! I will test\f + \fr 2:1 \ft The MT reads “I will test you,” but the BHS editors propose “I will test …” Whether or not one adopts MT, Qohelet is speaking to himself \f* pleasure ⸤to see whether it is worthwhile⸥.”\f + \fr 2:1 \ft Literally “and look at goodness”; this idiom refers to the enjoyment of life \f* But look, “This also \add is\add* vanity!” 
\v 2 I said of laughter, “\add It is\add* folly!” and of pleasure, “⸤What does it accomplish?⸥”\f + \fr 2:2 \ft Literally “What does it give?” \f* 
\v 3 I also ⸤explored⸥\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Literally “I searched in my mind” \f* ⸤the effects of indulging my flesh⸥\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Literally “to cheer my flesh” \f* with wine. My mind guiding me with wisdom, ⸤I investigated⸥\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Literally “laid hold of” \f* folly so that I might discover what \add is\add* good under heaven\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Follows MT; two medieval Hebrew manuscripts, LXX, Peshitta read, “under the sun,” cf. 1:3, 9, etc. \f* for ⸤humans⸥\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* to do ⸤during the days of their lives⸥.\f + \fr 2:3 \ft Literally “the number of the days of their lives” \f*
\s1 Qohelet’s Investigation of Personal Accomplishment
\m 
\v 4 ⸤I accomplished great things⸥.\f + \fr 2:4 \ft Literally “I made great my works” \f* I built for myself houses; I planted for myself vineyards. 
\v 5 I made for myself gardens and parks, and I planted all \add sorts of\add* fruit trees in them. 
\v 6 I made for myself pools of water from which to irrigate a grove of flourishing trees. 
\v 7 I acquired male slaves and female slaves, as well as children \add born in my\add* house. I also had livestock, cattle, and flocks more than anyone who \add was\add* before me in Jerusalem. 
\v 8 I also gathered to myself silver and gold—the royal and provincial treasuries. I acquired for myself male and female singers, as well as the delight of ⸤men⸥,\f + \fr 2:8 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* ⸤voluptuous concubines⸥.\f + \fr 2:8 \ft Literally “a breast and breasts,” as a synecdoche for beautiful women in the king’s harem \f*
\p 
\v 9 Thus, ⸤I accomplished far more⸥\f + \fr 2:9 \ft Literally “I became great and I surpassed” \f* than anyone who \add was\add* before me in Jerusalem—indeed, my wisdom stood by me. 
\v 10 I neither withheld anything from my eyes that they desired, nor did I deprive any pleasure from my heart. My heart rejoiced in all my toil, for this was my reward from all my toil. 
\v 11 Yet when I considered\f + \fr 2:11 \ft Or “turned to” \f* all the effort which I expended and the toil with which I toiled to do, then behold, “Everything \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind! There is nothing profitable under the sun!”
\s1 The Living Must Abandon the Work of their Hands to Others at Death
\m 
\v 12 Next, I considered wisdom, as well as delusion and folly. What can anyone \add do\add* who will come after the king that has not already been done? 
\v 13 I realized that wisdom has an advantage over folly, just as light has an advantage over darkness. 
\v 14 ⸤The wise man can see where he is walking⸥,\f + \fr 2:14 \ft Literally “The eyes of the wise \fq are \ft in his head” \f* but the fool walks in darkness. Yet I also realized that both of them suffer the same fate. 
\v 15 So I said ⸤to myself⸥,\f + \fr 2:15 \ft Literally “in my heart” \f* “⸤If I also suffer the same fate as the fool⸥,\f + \fr 2:15 \ft Literally “Just as the fate of the fool—so it will happen to me!” \f* ⸤what advantage is my great wisdom⸥?”\f + \fr 2:15 \ft Literally “why have I been so exceedingly wise?” \f* So I said ⸤to myself⸥,\f + \fr 2:15 \ft Literally “in my heart” \f* “This also \add is\add* vanity!”
\p 
\v 16 Certainly no one will remember the wise man or the fool in ⸤future generations⸥.\f + \fr 2:16 \ft Literally “the futures” \f* When \add future\add* days come, both will have been forgotten already. How \add is it that\add* the wise man dies the same as the fool? 
\v 17 So I hated life because the work done under the sun \add is\add* grievous to me. For everything \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind!
\p 
\v 18 So I hated all my toil with which I have toiled under the sun, for I must leave it behind to someone who will be after me. 
\v 19 And who knows \add whether\add* he will be wise or foolish? Yet he will exercise control of all \add the fruit of\add* my toil with which I toiled wisely under the sun. This also \add is\add* vanity!
\p 
\v 20 So ⸤I began to despair⸥\f + \fr 2:20 \ft Literally “I myself turned to cause my heart to despair” \f* of all the toil with which I toiled under the sun. 
\v 21 For although a person may toil with great wisdom and skill, he must leave his reward to someone who has not toiled for it. This also \add is\add* vanity and a great calamity. 
\v 22 For what does a person receive for all his toil and in the longing of his heart with which he toils under the sun? 
\v 23 All his days \add are\add* painful, his labor \add brings\add* grief, and his heart cannot rest at night. This also \add is\add* vanity!
\s1 It is Best to Simply Enjoy the Passing Pleasures of Life as Reward for Pleasing God
\m 
\v 24 There is nothing better for a person than to eat and drink and ⸤find delight⸥\f + \fr 2:24 \ft Literally “to see good” \f* in his toil. For I also realized that this \add is\add* from the hand of God! 
\v 25 For who can eat \add and drink\add*, and who can enjoy \add life\add* apart from him?\f + \fr 2:25 \ft The MT reads “more than me,” which is supported by Aramaic Targum and Latin Vulgate, but several medieval Hebrew manuscripts read “from him” \f* 
\v 26 For to the person who \add is\add* good in his eyes, he gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy; but to the sinner he gives the task of gathering and heaping up only to give \add it\add* to \add him who is\add* pleasing to him. This also \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind!
\c 3
\s1 God Has Ordained the Ebb and Flow of Human Activities
\m 
\v 1 For everything there \add is\add* an appointed time, a time for every matter under heaven:
\sd0
\q1 
\v 2 a time to bear\f + \fr 3:2 \ft Or “a time to be born”; MT reads the active form “to bear \fq children \ft ” \f* and a time to die;
\q2 a time to plant and a time to root up \add what is\add* planted;
\q1 
\v 3 a time to kill and a time to heal;
\q2 a time to break down and a time to build up;
\q1 
\v 4 a time to weep and a time to laugh;
\q2 a time to mourn and a time to dance;
\q1 
\v 5 a time to throw away stones and a time to gather stones;
\q2 a time to embrace and a time to refrain from embracing;
\q1 
\v 6 a time to seek and a time to lose;
\q2 a time to keep and a time to throw away;
\q1 
\v 7 a time to tear and a time to sew;
\q2 a time to be silent and a time to speak;
\q1 
\v 8 a time to love and a time to hate;
\q2 a time \add for\add* war and a time \add for\add* peace.
\sd0
\p 
\v 9 What does the worker gain in his toil?
\s1 No One Understands God’s Mysterious Plan
\m 
\v 10 I have seen the busyness God gives to ⸤humans⸥\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* to preoccupy\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Or “to be busy” \f* them. 
\v 11 He has made everything suitable in its time. He also has put ⸤the past⸥\f + \fr 3:11 \ft Literally “eternity” \f* in their hearts, yet no one can grasp what God does from the beginning to the end. 
\v 12 So I realized that there is ⸤nothing better⸥\f + \fr 3:12 \ft Literally “no good” \f* for them than to ⸤rejoice and enjoy themselves⸥\f + \fr 3:12 \ft Literally “to rejoice and to do good” \f* during their lives. 
\v 13 And for anyone to eat and drink, that is, ⸤to enjoy the fruit of all his toil⸥,\f + \fr 3:13 \ft Literally “to see good in all his toil” \f* this also is a gift of God.
\sd0
\q1 
\v 14 I know everything God does endures forever;
\q2 nothing can be added to it, and nothing can be taken from it,
\q3 for God so acts that humans\f + \fr 3:14 \ft Or “they” \f* might stand in awe before him.
\q1 
\v 15 What is—it already was,
\q2 and what will be—it already is,
\q3 for ⸤God will do what he has done.⸥\f + \fr 3:15 \ft Literally “God seeks \fq what \ft is pursued” \f*
\sd0
\s1 God’s Mysterious Plan Allows Injustice to Exist in the World
\m 
\v 16 I saw something else under the sun: instead of justice \add there was\add* evil; instead of righteousness \add there was\add* wickedness. 
\v 17 So I said ⸤to myself⸥,\f + \fr 3:17 \ft Literally “in my heart” \f* “God will surely judge the righteous and the wicked, for he has appointed\f + \fr 3:17 \ft The MT reads שָׁם “there,” but repointing to שָׂם, “he has appointed,” makes better sense \f* a time \add of judgment\add* for every deed and every work.”
\p 
\v 18 I said to myself concerning ⸤humans⸥,\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* “God sifts\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Or “tests” \f* them in order to show\f + \fr 3:18 \ft The MT reads active “to see,” but causative “to show” is reflected by LXX, Syriac Peshitta, and Latin Vulgate \f* them that they are like beasts.” 
\v 19 For the fate of ⸤humans⸥\f + \fr 3:19 \ft Literally “the sons of the man” \f* and the fate of the beast is ⸤the same⸥.\f + \fr 3:19 \ft Literally “\fq is \ft one” \f* The death of the one is like the death of the other, for ⸤both are mortal⸥.\f + \fr 3:19 \ft Literally “and one breath \fq is \ft for all” \f* Man has no advantage over the beast, for both are fleeting. 
\v 20 Both go to one place—both came from dust and both return to dust. 
\v 21 For no one knows \add whether\add* the spirit of a human ascends \add to heaven\add* and \add whether\add* the spirit of the beast descends to the ground!
\p 
\v 22 So I concluded that there is nothing better for a person than to enjoy \add the fruit of\add* his labor, for this is his lot in life. ⸤For no one knows what will happen in the future.⸥\f + \fr 3:22 \ft Literally “For who can bring him to see in what will be after him?” \f*
\c 4
\s1 The Existence of Oppression in the World Makes Human Existence Miserable
\m 
\v 1 I looked again, and I saw all the oppression that occurs under the sun.
\sd0
\q1 ⸤I saw the tears of the oppressed—
\q2 no one comforts them!
\q1 Those who oppress them are powerful—
\q2 no one can comfort them⸥!\f + \fr 4:1 \ft Literally “And look! The tears of the oppressed, and there is no comforting for them, and from the hand of oppressors \fq of \ft them \fq was \ft power, and there is no comforting for them” \f*
\q1 
\v 2 So I deemed the dead who have already died
\q2 more \add fortunate\add* than the living who are still alive.
\q1 
\v 3 But better \add off\add* than both of them is the one who has not yet been born
\q2 and has not seen the evil deeds that are done under the sun.
\sd0
\s1 People Need Balance in Their Approach to Labor
\m 
\v 4 I also realized that all \add of the\add* toil and all \add of\add* the skillful work that is done—it \add is\add* envy between one man and ⸤another⸥.\f + \fr 4:4 \ft Literally “his friend” \f* This also \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind!
\sd0
\q1 
\v 5 ⸤The fool refuses to work with his hands,
\q2 so he has nothing to eat except his own skin⸥!\f + \fr 4:5 \ft Literally “The fool folds his hands and eats his flesh” \f*
\q1 
\v 6 Better \add is\add* one handful with peace
\q2 than two fists full with toil and chasing wind.
\sd0
\s1 Wealth without Someone with Which to Enjoy It is Futile
\m 
\v 7 I turned again and saw another vanity under the sun. 
\v 8 Sometimes a man is all alone with no companion; he also has neither son nor brother. Yet there is no end to all his toil, and his eye is not satisfied with wealth. \add He laments,\add* “For whom am I toiling and depriving ⸤myself⸥\f + \fr 4:8 \ft Literally “his soul” \f* of pleasure?” This also \add is\add* vanity—it is an unhappy business!
\s1 Friends and Family Can Help One Another in Life
\m 
\v 9 Two \add are\add* better than the one, for they enjoy a better reward for their toil. 
\v 10 For if one falls, his companion may help him up. But pity the one who falls and there is ⸤no one⸥\f + \fr 4:10 \ft Literally “there is not a second” \f* to help him up. 
\v 11 Also if two lie together, ⸤they can keep each other warm⸥.\f + \fr 4:11 \ft Literally “and it will be warm for them” \f* But how can one person be warm? 
\v 12 ⸤Although an assailant may overpower one person, two may withstand him⸥.\f + \fr 4:12 \ft Literally “And even though he will prevail against him, the one; the second, they will withstand opposite him” \f* A threefold cord ⸤is not easily broken⸥!\f + \fr 4:12 \ft Literally “will not be broken in haste” \f*
\s1 One Must Be Willing to Listen to Counsel
\m 
\v 13 A poor but wise youth \add is\add* better than an old but foolish king who no longer knows ⸤how to receive advice⸥.\f + \fr 4:13 \ft Literally “how to be warned” \f* 
\v 14 For he came out of the prison house to reign, ⸤since he was born poor in his kingdom⸥.\f + \fr 4:14 \ft Literally “for all in his kingdom he was born poor” \f* 
\v 15 I saw all the living who move about under the sun with the youth; the second who will stand in his place. 
\v 16 There is no end to all the people, to all who were before him. Yet the later generation will not rejoice in him, for this also \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind!
\c 5
\s1 Listen to God Rather Than Uttering Rash Vows
\sd0
\q1 
\v 1 \f + \fr 5:1 \ft \xt Ecclesiastes 5:1–20 \ft in the English Bible is 4:17–5:19 in the Hebrew Bible \f* Guard your steps when you go to the house of God;
\q2 draw near to listen \add rather\add* than to offer a sacrifice of fools,
\q3 for they do not know that they are doing evil.
\q1 
\v 2 Do not be rash with your mouth,
\q2 and do not let your heart be quick to utter a word before God.
\q1 For God is in heaven, and you \add are\add* on earth;
\q2 therefore, let your words be few.
\q1 
\v 3 For a dream comes with many cares,
\q2 and the voice of a fool with many words.
\q1 
\v 4 When you make a vow to God,
\q2 do not delay in fulfilling it,
\q1 for ⸤he takes no pleasure⸥\f + \fr 5:4 \ft Literally “there is no desire” \f* in fools.
\q2 Fulfill what you vow!
\q1 
\v 5 It is better that you not vow
\q2 than that you vow and not fulfill it.
\q1 
\v 6 Do not let your mouth lead your flesh into sin,
\q2 and do not tell the messenger that it \add was\add* a mistake.
\q1 Why anger God at your words,
\q2 so that he destroys the work of your hands?
\q1 
\v 7 For with many dreams \add come\add* vanities and numerous words.
\q2 Therefore, fear God!
\sd0
\s1 Powerful Bureaucrats Exploit the Helpless Poor
\sd0
\q1 
\v 8 Do not be surprised if you see the poor being oppressed with violence
\q2 or \add do not see\add* justice and righteousness in the province.
\q1 For one official is watched by a higher official,
\q2 and \add there are\add* even higher officials over them!
\q1 
\v 9 The produce of the land is exploited by everyone;
\q2 ⸤even the king profits from the field \add of the poor\add*⸥!\f + \fr 5:9 \ft Literally “for the field is even worked for the king” \f*
\sd0
\s1 There is Never Enough Money to Satisfy
\sd0
\q1 
\v 10 Whoever loves money is not satisfied \add with\add* money,
\q2 and whoever loves wealth \add is\add* not \add satisfied with\add* profit.
\q1 This also \add is\add* vanity!
\q1 
\v 11 When prosperity increases,
\q2 those who consume it increase.
\q1 ⸤So its owner gains nothing,
\q2 except to see his wealth before it is spent⸥.\f + \fr 5:11 \ft Literally “And what gain has its owner but to see it with his eyes?” \f*
\q1 
\v 12 The sleep of the laborer \add is\add* pleasant, whether he eats little or much,
\q2 but the wealth of the rich man does not allow him to rest.
\sd0
\s1 Hoarding Wealth Can Backfire
\m 
\v 13 There is a grievous evil which I have seen under the sun: wealth ⸤hoarded⸥\f + \fr 5:13 \ft Literally “kept ” \f* by its owner to his harm. 
\v 14 That wealth was lost in a bad venture. Although he has borne a child, ⸤he has nothing to leave to him⸥.\f + \fr 5:14 \ft Literally “he has nothing in his hand” \f* 
\v 15 Just as he came from his mother’s womb naked, ⸤he will depart⸥\f + \fr 5:15 \ft Literally “return to go” \f* just as he came; he will take nothing with him for his toil. 
\v 16 This also \add is\add* a grievous illness. Exactly as he came, so he will go. What profit \add does\add* he gain for all his toil for the wind? 
\v 17 Also, he eats in darkness all his days; he is frustrated \add in\add* much sickness and resentment.
\s1 If You Have Wealth, Enjoy It as God Enables
\m 
\v 18 Look! I have discovered what is good and fitting: to eat and to drink and ⸤to enjoy⸥\f + \fr 5:18 \ft Literally “to see goodness” \f* all \add the fruit of\add* the toil with which one toils under the sun during the number of the days of his life that God gives to him—for this \add is\add* his lot.\f + \fr 5:18 \ft Or “fate” \f* 
\v 19 This indeed is a gift of God: everyone to whom God gives wealth and possessions, he also empowers him ⸤to enjoy them⸥,\f + \fr 5:19 \ft Literally “to eat from it” \f* to accept his lot, and to rejoice in \add the fruit of\add* his toil. 
\v 20 For he does not remember the \add brief\add* days of his life, for God keeps his heart preoccupied with enjoyment \add of life\add*.
\c 6
\s1 Those Who Have Wealth but Do Not Enjoy It Are Pitiful
\m 
\v 1 Here is another misfortune that I have seen under the sun, and it \add is\add* prevalent among humankind. 
\v 2 God gives a man wealth, possessions, and honor, so that he lacks nothing his heart desires; yet God does not enable him to enjoy it—instead someone else ends up enjoying it. This \add is\add* vanity—indeed, it \add is\add* a grievous ill!
\p 
\v 3 Even if a man fathers a hundred \add children\add* and lives many years so that the days of his years are many, if his heart\f + \fr 6:3 \ft Or “his soul” \f* is not satisfied with ⸤his prosperity⸥\f + \fr 6:3 \ft Literally “the good” \f* and ⸤he does not receive a proper burial⸥,\f + \fr 6:3 \ft Literally “and also there is no burial for him” \f* I deem the stillborn better than him. 
\v 4 For he comes into vanity and departs into darkness, and his name is shrouded in darkness. 
\v 5 He has neither seen nor known the sun, yet he has more rest than him. 
\v 6 Even if a man\f + \fr 6:6 \ft Hebrew “he” \f* lives a thousand years twice, if he\f + \fr 6:6 \ft Hebrew “and” \f* does not enjoy ⸤prosperity⸥,\f + \fr 6:6 \ft Literally “good” \f* ⸤both suffer the same fate⸥!\f + \fr 6:6 \ft Literally “are not the all going to the same place?” \f*
\s1 One Must Learn to Be Content with What One Has
\sd0
\q1 
\v 7 All of a man’s toil \add is\add* for his mouth—
\q2 yet his appetite is never satisfied.
\q1 
\v 8 So do the wise \add really\add* have an advantage over fools?
\q2 ⸤Can the poor \add really\add* gain anything by knowing how to act in front of others⸥?\f + \fr 6:8 \ft Literally “What \fq is there \ft for the poor knowing \fq how \ft to conduct themselves before the living?” \f*
\q1 
\v 9 ⸤Better to be content with what your eyes see
\q2 than for your soul to constantly crave more⸥.\f + \fr 6:9 \ft Literally “Sight of the eyes \fq is \ft better than wandering of desire” \f*
\q1 This also \add is\add* vanity and chasing wind!
\sd0
\s1 It is Futile for Humans to Complain about God’s Irresistible Will
\sd0
\q1 
\v 10 Whatever is—it was already determined,
\q2 ⸤what will be—it has already been decided⸥.\f + \fr 6:10 \ft Literally “and his name is known what he \fq is \ft man” \f*
\q1 As for man, he cannot argue
\q2 against what is more powerful than him.
\q1 
